‚Äãpyenv
‚ÄãFor a library or package, you might want to ignore these files since the code is
‚Äãintended to run in multiple environments; otherwise, check them in:
‚Äã.python-version
‚Äãpipenv
‚ÄãAccording to pypa/pipenv#598, it is recommended to include Pipfile.lock in version control.
‚ÄãHowever, in case of collaboration, if having platform-specific dependencies or dependencies
‚Äãhaving no cross-platform support, pipenv may install dependencies that don't work, or not
‚Äãinstall all needed dependencies.
‚Äã#Pipfile.lock
‚ÄãUV
‚ÄãSimilar to Pipfile.lock, it is generally recommended to include uv.lock in version control.
‚ÄãThis is especially recommended for binary packages to ensure reproducibility, and is more
‚Äãcommonly ignored for libraries.
‚Äã#uv.lock
‚Äãpoetry
‚ÄãSimilar to Pipfile.lock, it is generally recommended to include poetry.lock in version control.
‚ÄãThis is especially recommended for binary packages to ensure reproducibility, and is more
‚Äãcommonly ignored for libraries.
‚Äãhttps://python-poetry.org/docs/basic-usage/#commit-your-poetrylock-file-to-version-control
‚Äã#poetry.lock
#poetry.toml
‚Äãpdm
‚ÄãSimilar to Pipfile.lock, it is generally recommended to include pdm.lock in version control.
‚Äãpdm recommends including project-wide configuration in pdm.toml, but excluding .pdm-python.
‚Äãhttps://pdm-project.org/en/latest/usage/project/#working-with-version-control
‚Äã#pdm.lock
#pdm.toml
.pdm-python
.pdm-build/
‚Äãpixi
‚ÄãSimilar to Pipfile.lock, it is generally recommended to include pixi.lock in version control.
‚Äã#pixi.lock
‚ÄãPixi creates a virtual environment in the .pixi directory, just like venv module creates one
‚Äãin the .venv directory. It is recommended not to include this directory in version control.
‚Äã.pixi
‚ÄãPEP 582; used by e.g. github.com/David-OConnor/pyflow and github.com/pdm-project/pdm
